<TITLE> HC orders fugitive Mockbul to surrender </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 6 (bdnews24.com)-- The High Court has asked former Awami League MP Mockbul Hossain to surrender to a lower court within seven days in a corruption case. Hossain was convicted, in absentia, by a Special Judges' Court on May 9, 2008 for possessing illegal assets and sentenced to jail for 13 years. He has been absconding since then. The bench of justices Mohammad Shamsul Huda and Abu Bakar Siddiqui gave the order on Thursday following a bail petition made by Hossain through his lawyer. Abdul Matin Khasru argued for Hossain and attorney general Mahbubey Alam for the government. Former attorney general Mahmudul Islam was also present in court as a "friend of the court" - known as an Amicus Curiea - since someone absconding cannot formally make an appeal against their sentence or apply for bail. Deputy Anticorruption Commission director Akhter Hossain filed the corruption case with Mohammadpur police on Aug 16, 2007. bdnew
